              <fr:mainmatter>
                <html:p>Let <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\prec  \colon  A\mathbin {\nrightarrow } A]]></fr:tex> be a <fr:link href="/jms-00I7/" title="Relation" uri="https://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-00I7/" display-uri="jms-00I7" type="local">relation</fr:link> on a set <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[A]]></fr:tex>.</html:p>
                <html:ol><html:li>An element <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[m\in  S\subseteq  A]]></fr:tex> is a <html:em><html:strong><html:span style="white-space: nowrap"><fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\prec ]]></fr:tex>-minimal</html:span></html:strong></html:em> (henceforth, “minimal”) element of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[S]]></fr:tex> when <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\lnot {\mathopen {}\left (\exists  x\in  S\mathpunct {.} x\prec  m\right )\mathclose {}}]]></fr:tex>.</html:li>
 <html:li>The binary <fr:link href="/jms-00I7/" title="Relation" uri="https://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-00I7/" display-uri="jms-00I7" type="local">relation</fr:link> <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\prec ]]></fr:tex> on <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[A]]></fr:tex> is called <html:em><html:strong>well-founded</html:strong></html:em> whenever each non-empty subset of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[A]]></fr:tex> has a minimal element.</html:li></html:ol>
